547
00:49:57,560 --> 00:50:02,560
break down barriers and the conversation feels 
like it's flowing. It feels like a dinner table  

548
00:50:02,560 --> 00:50:07,320
conversation versus a hard conversation, even 
if it might be something about something tough. 

549
00:50:07,320 --> 00:50:14,840
So I think to me, there's this concept of, 
you might still be faced with this challenge  

550
00:50:14,840 --> 00:50:23,840
of I'm not sure what the right decision is, and 
I'm struggling to really do this analysis and  

551
00:50:23,840 --> 00:50:30,800
really get something going. I think accepting 
that that happens to everyone, it sort of feels  

552
00:50:30,800 --> 00:50:36,120
like a product block as opposed to a writer's 
block, if that makes sense. Where as a writer,  

553
00:50:36,120 --> 00:50:41,920
you might be trying to get to that next paragraph, 
and as a product manager, you're really trying to  

554
00:50:41,920 --> 00:50:47,320
get to that next idea or that next milestone.
So I can give you an example there as well,  

555
00:50:47,320 --> 00:50:53,840
which is we had this moment a little over a year 
ago where we were not sure which direction to take  

556
00:50:53,840 --> 00:50:59,880
a product feature. And we were faced with 
this decision that felt pretty existential,  

557
00:50:59,880 --> 00:51:07,880
which is how much do we want to invest in LLMs 
and the new wave of large language model tech  

558
00:51:07,880 --> 00:51:13,400
versus what our existing customer base was. And 
it wasn't immediately clear what the decision  

559
00:51:13,400 --> 00:51:20,000
should be. And so the energy I just brought was, 
I'm just going to be our outbound salesperson and  

560
00:51:20,000 --> 00:51:24,960
just start writing LinkedIn messages to people 
that have the title AI in their LinkedIn profile.  

561
00:51:24,960 --> 00:51:29,120
So I just went on LinkedIn and literally just 
started finding ways to get them on a phone call.  

562
00:51:29,120 --> 00:51:35,160
So I'd write some copy and iterate on it, and 
I had to sit with our sales team to understand  

563
00:51:35,160 --> 00:51:40,040
how do you do this? I maxed out my five LinkedIn 
messages a day, what are you trying to do here? 

564
00:51:40,040 --> 00:51:45,880
And I think what that really accomplished was 
sort of two things. One, I did learn a little  

565
00:51:45,880 --> 00:51:53,080
bit of what goes into this role in terms of how 
to message our problem and product more in a way  

566
00:51:53,080 --> 00:51:58,560
that actually got people engaged? But two, it also 
demonstrated to the team that I was willing to get  

567
00:51:58,560 --> 00:52:04,360
into the details with them. I was willing to spend 
time even when I was trying to push on our day job  

568
00:52:04,360 --> 00:52:09,960
of building a product and keeping it growing. 
And I think that counts for a lot when the team  

569
00:52:09,960 --> 00:52:15,040
is already feeling like they're not sure which 
direction to take something. And so just being  

570
00:52:15,040 --> 00:52:20,560
that player coach and just having that mentality 
of showing up, bringing the energy, can move the  

571
00:52:20,560 --> 00:52:25,720
bar so much higher for the whole team to operate.
So that's the example I give of, you're kind of  

572
00:52:25,720 --> 00:52:31,880
like being LeBron James, you're coaching people, 
you're drawing up the play, but you're also just  

573
00:52:31,880 --> 00:52:38,720
trying to be as involved in all of the tough 
stuff as well. And I see that happen, I think that  

574
00:52:38,720 --> 00:52:44,360
really comes from leadership from our CEO as well, 
he'll be tired, I can tell, but it's just when  

575
00:52:44,360 --> 00:52:48,640
he shows up to a meeting, he just doesn't show 
it. You just have to kind of bring that energy.

576
00:52:48,640 --> 00:52:50,840
So what I'm hearing is there's 
two things you're sharing here,  

577
00:52:50,840 --> 00:52:56,560
which is awesome. So one is, there's actual 
energy in a meeting of staying positive  

578
00:52:56,560 --> 00:53:01,520
and energetic. And then two is actually 
just doing the thing to figure help solve  

579
00:53:01,520 --> 00:53:07,000
the problem, getting into sales, becoming 
the salesperson potentially, reaching out,  

580
00:53:07,000 --> 00:53:11,120
doing customer development in your own, kind of 
going rogue a little bit. In that first bucket,  

581
00:53:11,120 --> 00:53:16,240
what does it look like to bring the energy? 
Is it just volume? Is it just being bright?

582
00:53:16,240 --> 00:53:20,200
I actually think this depends a lot on the 
person. I think that's actually a personal  

583
00:53:20,200 --> 00:53:26,800
thing. So what I mean by that is, for 
me, that might mean I'm showing up,  

584
00:53:26,800 --> 00:53:33,280
I'm super enthused, I'm bringing my version of 
energy. But to other people, that might mean  

585
00:53:33,280 --> 00:53:39,320
smaller things like just asking how someone is 
doing, trying to keep the tone of the meeting  

586
00:53:39,320 --> 00:53:44,480
more positive, I think to some degree. So to 
different people, that might resemble different  

587
00:53:44,480 --> 00:53:50,640
things. But I actually think this comes back 
a little bit to an earlier point of, humans  

588
00:53:50,640 --> 00:53:56,000
are really good at picking up on these subtle 
signals with other people. And you want to just  

589
00:53:56,000 --> 00:54:02,640
be putting out this subtle energy where people 
feel like you are engaged, you're in it 100%. 

590
00:54:02,640 --> 00:54:09,040
So I think that's part of it, I think it's 
the idea's for other people to feel like  

591
00:54:10,440 --> 00:54:13,840
you're bringing the energy level of 
the room up versus bringing it down.

592
00:54:13,840 --> 00:54:17,760
I had a PM I was working with at one 
point that is the epitome of that.  

593
00:54:17,760 --> 00:54:21,560
Every meeting he walks into, he's 
just like, solve some problems,  

594
00:54:21,560 --> 00:54:28,320
let's do this. He comes in just positive and 
energized and that just changes the whole feeling.

595
00:54:28,320 --> 00:54:32,960
I remember this early Lyft anecdote, I have 
some friends from the earlier days at Lyft,  

596
00:54:32,960 --> 00:54:38,080
and I think this may have been in the self-driving 
car division, but they would literally, I'm not  

597
00:54:38,080 --> 00:54:44,600
even kidding, this was their ritual where they 
would actually end the meetings with the phrase,  

598
00:54:44,600 --> 00:54:49,160
make it happen. And I thought that was 
so powerful, because it's so simple,  

599
00:54:49,160 --> 00:54:51,720
but it's like, all right, we're going 
to do this. It was one of their values,  

600
00:54:51,720 --> 00:54:55,760
and we walk away from a decision 
and we're going to make it happen. 

601
00:54:55,760 --> 00:55:00,080
And I think even just as something as small 
